				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">ROM emulators always were obscure items. Really to make your own wouldn't cost you very much, the only significant cost would be the PCB. But if you do make your own, you can tailor it to the SNES, or generic ROM, or both. I have designed some (not built) as exercises in the past, and for a simple single 8-bit ROM emulator you could get by on $3 of logic, paired with a &lt;=$40 PCB, and &lt;=$3 parallel port connector, &lt;=$2 CR2032 cell, &lt;$1 analog to build one from $50 of parts before the SRAM.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

